<section class="section" style="background-color: var(--light-color);">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Menstrual Cycle Basics</h2>
    
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-lg-6">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">What is the Menstrual Cycle?</h4>
            <p>The menstrual cycle is a series of natural changes in hormone production and the structures of the uterus and ovaries that make pregnancy possible. The average cycle length is 28 days, but it can range from 21 to 35 days.</p>
            <p>The cycle is regulated by hormones from the brain (follicle-stimulating hormone and luteinizing hormone) and the ovaries (estrogen and progesterone).</p>
            <p>Understanding your menstrual cycle helps you:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Predict when your period will occur</li>
              <li>Identify your fertile window if trying to conceive</li>
              <li>Recognize when something might be abnormal</li>
              <li>Better understand your body's patterns and changes</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-lg-6">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">The Four Phases</h4>
            <ol>
              <li><strong>Menstrual Phase (Days 1-5):</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>The uterine lining sheds through the vagina as a period</li>
                  <li>Day 1 of bleeding is considered day 1 of the cycle</li>
                  <li>Typically lasts 3-7 days</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Follicular Phase (Days 1-13):</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Overlaps with the menstrual phase</li>
                  <li>Follicles (egg sacs) in the ovaries begin to mature</li>
                  <li>Estrogen levels rise</li>
                  <li>The uterine lining starts to thicken</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Ovulation (Day 14, approximately):</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>A mature egg is released from an ovary</li>
                  <li>The egg travels down the fallopian tube</li>
                  <li>Can be accompanied by mild pain or spotting</li>
                  <li>This is the most fertile time</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Luteal Phase (Days 15-28):</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>The ruptured follicle forms the corpus luteum</li>
                  <li>Progesterone levels rise</li>
                  <li>The uterine lining continues to thicken</li>
                  <li>If pregnancy doesn't occur, hormone levels drop and the cycle begins again</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Sexual Health Topics</h2>
    
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4 mb-4">
        <div class="info-card h-100">
          <div class="info-card-content">
            <h4>Consent and Communication</h4>
            <p>Healthy sexual relationships are built on clear consent and open communication.</p>
            <h5 class="mt-3">Key principles of consent:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Freely given - without pressure, manipulation, or under the influence of substances</li>
              <li>Reversible - can be withdrawn at any time</li>
              <li>Informed - all parties understand what's involved</li>
              <li>Enthusiastic - all parties genuinely want to participate</li>
              <li>Specific - saying yes to one activity doesn't mean yes to others</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Communication about boundaries, desires, and protection is essential for a satisfying and safe sexual experience.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4 mb-4">
        <div class="info-card h-100">
          <div class="info-card-content">
            <h4>Sexually Transmitted Infections (STIs)</h4>
            <p>STIs are infections that can be transmitted through sexual contact. Common STIs include:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Chlamydia</li>
              <li>Gonorrhea</li>
              <li>Herpes</li>
              <li>Human Papillomavirus (HPV)</li>
              <li>Syphilis</li>
              <li>HIV</li>
              <li>Trichomoniasis</li>
            </ul>
            <h5 class="mt-3">Prevention:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Use barriers (condoms, dental dams) during sexual activity</li>
              <li>Get vaccinated against HPV and hepatitis B</li>
              <li>Get regular STI testing</li>
              <li>Communicate with partners about sexual health</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4 mb-4">
        <div class="info-card h-100">
          <div class="info-card-content">
            <h4>Pleasure and Sexual Well-being</h4>
            <p>Sexual pleasure is an important aspect of overall well-being. Understanding your body and what brings you pleasure is healthy and normal.</p>
            <h5 class="mt-3">Components of sexual well-being:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Physical pleasure and satisfaction</li>
              <li>Emotional connection and intimacy</li>
              <li>Body confidence and self-acceptance</li>
              <li>Freedom from shame or anxiety</li>
              <li>Ability to communicate needs and boundaries</li>
            </ul>
            <p>If you experience pain, discomfort, or concerns related to sexual function, consult with a healthcare provider. Many sexual difficulties can be addressed with proper care.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" style="background-color: var(--light-color);">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Common Reproductive Health Concerns</h2>
    
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Irregular Periods</h4>
            <p>Menstrual cycles that are consistently shorter than 21 days or longer than 35 days, or that vary significantly from month to month.</p>
            <h5>Possible causes:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Hormonal imbalances</li>
              <li>Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS)</li>
              <li>Thyroid disorders</li>
              <li>Extreme weight loss or gain</li>
              <li>Excessive exercise</li>
              <li>Stress</li>
              <li>Perimenopause</li>
              <li>Certain medications</li>
            </ul>
            <p>When to see a doctor: If your periods are consistently irregular, very painful, or if you miss three or more periods in a row (and aren't pregnant).</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Pelvic Pain</h4>
            <p>Pain in the lower abdomen that may be sharp, cramping, intermittent, or constant.</p>
            <h5>Possible causes:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Menstrual cramps</li>
              <li>Ovulation pain</li>
              <li>Endometriosis</li>
              <li>Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID)</li>
              <li>Fibroids</li>
              <li>Ovarian cysts</li>
              <li>Urinary tract infection</li>
              <li>Gastrointestinal issues</li>
            </ul>
            <p>When to see a doctor: If pain is severe, persistent, or accompanied by fever, vomiting, abnormal vaginal discharge, or if it disrupts daily activities.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Vaginal Infections</h4>
            <p>Infections that cause changes in vaginal discharge, odor, itching, or discomfort.</p>
            <h5>Common types:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Bacterial Vaginosis (BV):</strong> Overgrowth of certain bacteria, causing fishy odor and thin, gray discharge</li>
              <li><strong>Yeast Infections:</strong> Fungal infection causing thick, white discharge and intense itching</li>
              <li><strong>Trichomoniasis:</strong> Sexually transmitted infection causing greenish-yellow discharge, itching, and burning</li>
            </ul>
            <p>When to see a doctor: If you have abnormal discharge, especially with strong odor, itching, burning, or pain during urination or intercourse.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Fertility Concerns</h4>
            <p>Difficulty conceiving after 12 months of regular, unprotected intercourse (or 6 months if woman is over 35).</p>
            <h5>Possible factors:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Age (female fertility declines after 30, more significantly after 35)</li>
              <li>Irregular ovulation</li>
              <li>Blocked fallopian tubes</li>
              <li>Endometriosis</li>
              <li>Uterine or cervical conditions</li>
              <li>Male factors (low sperm count or motility)</li>
              <li>Lifestyle factors (smoking, alcohol, weight)</li>
            </ul>
            <p>When to see a doctor: If you've been trying to conceive for 12 months (or 6 months if over 35) without success, or if you have known factors that might affect fertility.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="text-center mb-5">Preventive Care Recommendations</h2>
    
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-lg-10 mx-auto">
        <div class="table-responsive">
          <table class="table table-striped">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Age Group</th>
                <th>Recommended Screenings</th>
                <th>Frequency</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>21-29 years</td>
                <td>Pap smear (cervical cancer screening)</td>
                <td>Every 3 years</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>30-65 years</td>
                <td>Pap smear and HPV test (co-testing)</td>
                <td>Every 5 years (or Pap alone every 3 years)</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>All sexually active women</td>
                <td>STI testing</td>
                <td>Annually or with new partners</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Women with risk factors</td>
                <td>Testing for chlamydia and gonorrhea</td>
                <td>Annually through age 24, then as recommended</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>40+ years</td>
                <td>Mammogram (breast cancer screening)</td>
                <td>Annually or biennially based on risk factors</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>45+ years</td>
                <td>Colonoscopy (colorectal cancer screening)</td>
                <td>Every 10 years or as recommended based on results</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>All adult women</td>
                <td>Blood pressure screening</td>
                <td>At least every 2 years</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>All adult women</td>
                <td>Cholesterol screening</td>
                <td>Every 4-6 years, or as recommended</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        
        <div class="alert alert-info mt-4">
          <p class="mb-0"><strong>Note:</strong> These are general guidelines. Your healthcare provider may recommend different screening schedules based on your personal and family health history, risk factors, and previous test results.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" style="background-color: var(--light-color);">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="text-center mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    
    <div class="accordion" id="reproductiveFAQ">
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingOne">
          <button class="accordion-button" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseOne" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="collapseOne">
            What should I do if my period is irregular?
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div id="collapseOne" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" aria-labelledby="headingOne" data-bs-parent="#reproductiveFAQ">
          <div class="accordion-body">
            If your periods are consistently irregular (cycles shorter than 21 days or longer than 35 days, or varying significantly), it's worth discussing with your healthcare provider. While some variation is normal, persistent irregularity may indicate underlying conditions like polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), thyroid disorders, or hormonal imbalances. 
            
            In the meantime, tracking your periods using our menstrual cycle tracker can help identify patterns and provide valuable information for your healthcare provider. Lifestyle factors like extreme stress, significant weight changes, or excessive exercise can also affect your cycle, so addressing these may help.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingTwo">
          <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseTwo" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseTwo">
            How do I know if my vaginal discharge is normal?
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div id="collapseTwo" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingTwo" data-bs-parent="#reproductiveFAQ">
          <div class="accordion-body">
            Normal vaginal discharge varies in consistency and amount throughout your menstrual cycle due to hormonal changes. Healthy discharge is usually clear to white, may be stretchy, creamy, or watery, and has a mild or no odor. It typically increases around ovulation and before your period.
            
            Signs that may indicate an infection include:
            <ul>
              <li>Change in color (yellow, green, gray)</li>
              <li>Cottage cheese-like texture</li>
              <li>Strong or foul odor</li>
              <li>Accompanied by itching, burning, pain, or redness</li>
              <li>Significant increase in amount</li>
            </ul>
            
            If you notice these changes, especially if accompanied by discomfort, consult with a healthcare provider. Many vaginal infections are easily treatable with medication.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingThree">
          <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseThree" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseThree">
            How often should I get a Pap smear?
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div id="collapseThree" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingThree" data-bs-parent="#reproductiveFAQ">
          <div class="accordion-body">
            Current guidelines recommend:
            <ul>
              <li>Ages 21-29: Pap smear every 3 years</li>
              <li>Ages 30-65: Pap smear and HPV co-testing every 5 years (preferred) OR Pap smear alone every 3 years</li>
              <li>After 65: Can stop screening if you've had adequate prior screening with normal results</li>
            </ul>
            
            However, these are general guidelines. Your healthcare provider may recommend a different schedule based on your risk factors, such as:
            <ul>
              <li>History of abnormal Pap results</li>
              <li>HIV infection</li>
              <li>Weakened immune system</li>
              <li>Exposure to DES (diethylstilbestrol) before birth</li>
              <li>History of cervical cancer</li>
            </ul>
            
            Even if you don't need annual Pap smears, regular gynecological exams are still important for overall reproductive health.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingFour">
          <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseFour" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseFour">
            What can I do about painful periods?
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div id="collapseFour" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingFour" data-bs-parent="#reproductiveFAQ">
          <div class="accordion-body">
            Many women experience some discomfort during menstruation, but severe pain that interferes with daily activities isn't normal and may indicate conditions like endometriosis, fibroids, or adenomyosis. Here are strategies to manage period pain:
            
            <h5 class="mt-3">Home remedies:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Over-the-counter pain relievers like ibuprofen or naproxen (start taking before pain becomes severe)</li>
              <li>Heat therapy (heating pad or warm bath)</li>
              <li>Gentle exercise like walking or yoga</li>
              <li>Relaxation techniques and adequate rest</li>
              <li>Avoiding alcohol, caffeine, and salty foods that can worsen bloating and discomfort</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h5 class="mt-3">Medical treatments your doctor might recommend:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Hormonal birth control methods to regulate periods and reduce pain</li>
              <li>Prescription-strength pain relievers</li>
              <li>Treatment for underlying conditions if present</li>
            </ul>
            
            If period pain is severe, gets worse over time, or doesn't respond to over-the-counter medicine, consult with a healthcare provider.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

